74
00:06:18,760 --> 00:06:21,020
As long as we hold
our end of the bargain,

75
00:06:21,072 --> 00:06:21,587
they'll hold.

76
00:06:21,869 --> 00:06:24,189
Yeah, that wasn't what I meant.

77
00:06:25,026 --> 00:06:27,326
I understood a war meant
to antagonize England

78
00:06:27,361 --> 00:06:28,327
to frighten them,

79
00:06:28,362 --> 00:06:32,331
to prevent them from
moving against Nassau.

80
00:06:32,366 --> 00:06:35,334
But that isn't what we're
talking about anymore, is it?

81
00:06:35,369 --> 00:06:37,703
Now you're talking about
a war meant to be won.

82
00:06:39,707 --> 00:06:42,341
You convinced them.

83
00:06:42,376 --> 00:06:45,511
Convinced Scott, his wife, their people,

84
00:06:45,546 --> 00:06:49,048
our people, even Silver.

85
00:06:49,050 --> 00:06:50,766
But not you.

86
00:06:52,303 --> 00:06:54,853
Everyone's wrong but you.

87
00:06:57,775 --> 00:06:59,858
Maybe.

88
00:06:59,894 --> 00:07:02,811
<i>MAN: Captain! Masts!</i>

89
00:07:12,573 --> 00:07:13,739
Captain.

90
00:07:17,628 --> 00:07:22,331
Ocracoke Island. Teach is there.

91
00:07:22,383 --> 00:07:25,834
A few hours' time, assuming he's there,

92
00:07:25,886 --> 00:07:27,252
I'm going to begin a discussion

93
00:07:27,304 --> 00:07:28,754
in which I'm going to
ask him for something

94
00:07:28,806 --> 00:07:31,673
that he can't possibly give.

95
00:07:31,726 --> 00:07:33,726
And the success or failure of this war

96
00:07:33,761 --> 00:07:35,761
will depend upon the outcome.

97
00:07:37,681 --> 00:07:39,148
In a few hours' time,

98
00:07:39,183 --> 00:07:41,817
there's a good chance you're
going to look awfully smart.

99
00:07:55,116 --> 00:07:57,783
- [shouting]
- [laughing]

100
00:07:57,835 --> 00:07:59,535
<i>MAN: What are you doing?</i>

101
00:07:59,587 --> 00:08:01,086
[men shouting]

102
00:08:01,122 --> 00:08:02,755
<i>MAN: Bring him down!</i>

103
00:08:02,790 --> 00:08:04,923
<i>[laughter]</i>

104
00:08:08,629 --> 00:08:11,463
[shouting continues]

105
00:08:22,643 --> 00:08:23,892
<i>WOMAN: You look good.</i>

106
00:08:23,944 --> 00:08:25,811
As handsome as ever.

107
00:08:25,813 --> 00:08:28,147
You always were a gifted liar.

108
00:08:30,818 --> 00:08:33,368
When you were still pirating,

109
00:08:33,404 --> 00:08:35,954
I was the woman who
was Blackbeard's woman.

110
00:08:35,990 --> 00:08:39,374
Put my services in great demand

111
00:08:39,410 --> 00:08:43,212
all men wanting what
notorious men already had.

112
00:08:45,666 --> 00:08:47,082
And then you leave

113
00:08:47,134 --> 00:08:49,501
and my business fades.

114
00:08:51,472 --> 00:08:53,639
It's always the little
people who get hurt the worst

115
00:08:53,674 --> 00:08:55,340
when the market turns.

116
00:09:03,567 --> 00:09:06,685
<i>So when are you going to tell me?</i>

117
00:09:06,737 --> 00:09:07,853
Tell you what?

118
00:09:07,855 --> 00:09:09,905
What he's doing here.

119
00:09:10,941 --> 00:09:12,357
Charles?

120
00:09:15,946 --> 00:09:19,248
I remember when he had
forced you from Nassau.

121
00:09:19,283 --> 00:09:20,949
I remember how angry you were,

122
00:09:21,001 --> 00:09:23,035
how disappointed.

123
00:09:23,087 --> 00:09:24,286
And I remember you telling me

124
00:09:24,338 --> 00:09:25,954
that you'd never make
the same mistake again,

125
00:09:26,006 --> 00:09:28,790
that you had learned the hard way

126
00:09:28,843 --> 00:09:30,959
that only God made sons.

127
00:09:31,846 --> 00:09:33,378
Things are different now.

128
00:09:33,430 --> 00:09:35,464
Different how?

129
00:09:35,516 --> 00:09:37,516
Doesn't need to last long.

130
00:09:45,559 --> 00:09:48,360
A little Spanish shrapnel.

131
00:09:48,395 --> 00:09:52,064
It went in here when I was
not much older than him.

132
00:09:52,066 --> 00:09:56,068
Once in a while it migrates,

133
00:09:56,070 --> 00:09:59,988
ticks closer to reaching its terminus

134
00:10:00,040 --> 00:10:02,958
and striking its chime.

135
00:10:02,993 --> 00:10:06,128
Grim little timepiece

136
00:10:06,163 --> 00:10:09,915
whose ticking has grown
louder to my ears of late.

137
00:10:12,386 --> 00:10:14,503
Charles doesn't know, does he?

138
00:10:17,808 --> 00:10:19,091
<i>MAN: Captain!</i>

139
00:10:19,093 --> 00:10:21,343
<i>[man shouting]</i>

140
00:10:37,745 --> 00:10:39,161
Jesus.

141
00:10:44,084 --> 00:10:45,534
Welcome to Ocracoke.

142
00:10:50,374 --> 00:10:53,091
- [crowd chattering]
- [goat bleating]

143
00:10:53,127 --> 00:10:55,294
<i>HUDSON: At first I was tempted,</i>

144
00:10:55,296 --> 00:10:58,046
but in the end it felt wrong

145
00:10:58,098 --> 00:11:00,299
to betray the governor that way.

146
00:11:02,102 --> 00:11:04,269
And it felt dangerous...

147
00:11:05,773 --> 00:11:07,389
so I declined.

148
00:11:08,192 --> 00:11:09,858
Then how did this happen?

149
00:11:10,978 --> 00:11:12,861
How does an honest chambermaid

150
00:11:12,896 --> 00:11:14,529
end up in the employ
of the Spanish empire?

151
00:11:22,156 --> 00:11:24,790
A few days after I
declined their offer...

152
00:11:28,545 --> 00:11:30,829
I came home late from
the governor's service.

153
00:11:33,584 --> 00:11:36,501
It wasn't unusual for me to return home

154
00:11:36,503 --> 00:11:40,472
to find my children
long since fast asleep.

155
00:11:40,507 --> 00:11:44,309
That night, my children were not alone.

156
00:11:44,345 --> 00:11:47,980
<i>The man who had approached me</i>

157
00:11:48,015 --> 00:11:51,099
<i>Grandal... was there... </i>

158
00:11:51,852 --> 00:11:53,652
waiting.

159
00:11:55,572 --> 00:11:57,022
In his left hand, a knife.

160
00:11:57,074 --> 00:11:59,324
In his right, a purse.

161
00:12:02,746 --> 00:12:06,581
He said my children would receive
something from him that night.

162
00:12:08,669 --> 00:12:11,503
<i>He asked me to choose which.</i>

163
00:12:14,842 --> 00:12:17,376
These are the people
whom I am beholden to.

164
00:12:17,428 --> 00:12:20,679
This is what they are capable of doing.

165
00:12:22,683 --> 00:12:24,516
I cannot imagine what they will do

166
00:12:24,551 --> 00:12:26,802
if the cache is not returned whole.

167
00:12:38,065 --> 00:12:39,398
Ship's manifest, sir.

168
00:12:39,400 --> 00:12:40,732
The entirety of the gold from the fort

169
00:12:40,734 --> 00:12:42,734
is now stowed and ready
for transport to Havana.

170
00:12:42,736 --> 00:12:44,903
We should be under way within the hour.

171
00:12:44,955 --> 00:12:46,571
Put it in my office, please.

172
00:12:52,746 --> 00:12:54,379
I just left Miss Hudson.

173
00:12:57,051 --> 00:12:59,584
I had the instinct once or twice,

174
00:12:59,586 --> 00:13:02,254
the way she'd been watching me of late.

175
00:13:02,256 --> 00:13:04,139
I dismissed it,

176
00:13:04,174 --> 00:13:05,640
just assumed it related to some concern

177
00:13:05,676 --> 00:13:08,760
over my relationship with you
and its becoming inappropriate.

178
00:13:11,348 --> 00:13:12,764
What did she say?

179
00:13:13,984 --> 00:13:15,767
Did she report that
we're earnestly attempting

180
00:13:15,769 --> 00:13:17,018
to find and return the missing money?

181
00:13:17,071 --> 00:13:20,405
It's not about the money
for them, not anymore.

182
00:13:20,441 --> 00:13:23,658
When the gold from the Urca
was stolen, it was bad enough.

183
00:13:23,694 --> 00:13:25,577
Now they hear the
gold is being converted

184
00:13:25,612 --> 00:13:27,579
into something more
easily hidden from them,

185
00:13:27,614 --> 00:13:30,031
more easily smuggled away.

186
00:13:30,084 --> 00:13:33,835
That isn't theft. It's an insult.

187
00:13:33,871 --> 00:13:36,872
And insults to empires require answers.

188
00:13:40,177 --> 00:13:42,210
So it's personal, then?

189
00:13:44,131 --> 00:13:47,632
A binary question of my trustworthiness.

190
00:13:47,634 --> 00:13:51,853
Either I return the full
cache and prove it or I fail,

191
00:13:51,889 --> 00:13:54,606
and in trying to excuse the shortfall,

192
00:13:54,641 --> 00:13:56,057
only aggravate their existing suspicion

193
00:13:56,110 --> 00:13:59,611
that I am part of the pirate
problem, not its solution.

194
00:13:59,646 --> 00:14:02,614
And the dread fleet in Havana
sets sail the very next day

195
00:14:02,649 --> 00:14:04,900
to raze all of Nassau to the ground.

196
00:14:04,952 --> 00:14:08,904
Then we'll fight them,
defend the island.

197
00:14:08,956 --> 00:14:11,206
The odds would be dire, but
we are not without resources.

198
00:14:11,241 --> 00:14:12,574
No, not "we."

199
00:14:12,626 --> 00:14:14,576
I mean, someone might fight
them, but it won't be you and I.

200
00:14:14,628 --> 00:14:16,495
If the result of my endeavor here

201
00:14:16,547 --> 00:14:18,880
is a Spanish attack
against British forces,

202
00:14:18,916 --> 00:14:21,666
an act that threatens to
drag the empire into a war,

203
00:14:21,718 --> 00:14:24,336
I would be recalled to London
and likely debtors' prison

204
00:14:24,388 --> 00:14:27,005
and your capital sentence
would be reinstated.

205
00:14:27,007 --> 00:14:30,675
Now, I believe Nassau's best chance
at survival is with me guiding it.

206
00:14:30,677 --> 00:14:33,678
But if we cannot find Jack
Rackham and Anne Bonny,

207
00:14:33,680 --> 00:14:35,897
if we can't find the
cache in their possession,

208
00:14:35,933 --> 00:14:39,484
whatever happens to Nassau,
you and I are likely finished.

209
00:14:43,323 --> 00:14:44,573
<i>[metal clanging]</i>

210
00:14:44,608 --> 00:14:48,076
- <i>[crowd chattering]
- [chickens clucking]</i>

211
00:14:57,788 --> 00:14:59,371
Pardon me, gentlemen, if
you don't mind me asking,

212
00:14:59,423 --> 00:15:01,256
where is this wagon headed?

213
00:15:01,291 --> 00:15:04,209
To the fort.

214
00:15:04,261 --> 00:15:05,794
To do what, exactly?

215
00:15:05,846 --> 00:15:07,462
To fix it.

216
00:15:10,184 --> 00:15:11,883
I see.

217
00:15:13,554 --> 00:15:15,387
Just you two on the job, is it?

218
00:15:15,389 --> 00:15:17,055
A whole gang of us up there.

219
00:15:17,107 --> 00:15:19,441
Governor wants it shipshape
by the end of the month.

220
00:15:19,476 --> 00:15:20,942
[grunts]

221
00:15:23,063 --> 00:15:25,730
Suppose that fort's not
going to rebuild itself.

222
00:15:30,621 --> 00:15:33,989
[scoffs] No, I suppose it won't.

223
00:15:43,750 --> 00:15:46,418
[whistles] Hold still.

224
00:15:48,255 --> 00:15:49,754
There.

225
00:15:50,924 --> 00:15:53,475
<i>Well? What do you think?</i>

226
00:15:53,510 --> 00:15:56,678
You mean aside from the tit curtains?

227
00:15:56,730 --> 00:15:59,147
It's called a cravat.

228
00:16:00,601 --> 00:16:01,238
You want to fit in with them, right?

229
00:16:01,374 --> 00:16:04,569
- This is what they wear.
- "They" who?

230
00:16:04,605 --> 00:16:07,022
Respectable men.

231
00:16:09,109 --> 00:16:10,442
[groans]

232
00:16:10,444 --> 00:16:11,910
All right, yeah.

233
00:16:14,781 --> 00:16:16,615
- <i>[fiddle playing]</i>
- Place of birth?

234
00:16:16,667 --> 00:16:17,782
<i>MAN: Bristol.</i>

235
00:16:17,834 --> 00:16:19,367
- <i>[crowd chattering]
- Occupation?</i>

236
00:16:19,867 --> 00:16:20,995
<i>MAN: Ship's carpenter.</i>

237
00:16:22,122 --> 00:16:25,874
- <i>Ship served?</i>
- I used to serve the Buccaneer.

238
00:16:25,926 --> 00:16:27,342
Sign here.

239
00:16:27,377 --> 00:16:29,461
<i>[fiddle continues]</i>

240
00:16:29,463 --> 00:16:32,297
<i>Move on. Next?</i>

241
00:16:32,349 --> 00:16:34,466
What the fuck are you doing here?

242
00:16:36,436 --> 00:16:38,386
It's a cravat.

243
00:16:38,438 --> 00:16:39,804
It's what respectable men wear.

244
00:16:39,856 --> 00:16:42,350
It's... never mind what it is.

245
00:16:42,845 --> 00:16:43,717
You're supposed to be long gone by now.

246
00:16:44,275 --> 00:16:44,910
Why'd you come back?

247
00:16:45,312 --> 00:16:46,311
Where we're going,

248
00:16:46,363 --> 00:16:48,766
it seemed better to have
one of these than not.

249
00:16:49,033 --> 00:16:50,120
I thought as an added prize,

250
00:16:50,451 --> 00:16:52,317
I'd at least be able
to see it for myself,

251
00:16:52,369 --> 00:16:53,985
the new governor up to his ears

252
00:16:54,037 --> 00:16:55,787
in the very same bullshit
in which I've been drowning

253
00:16:55,822 --> 00:16:57,489
for the past few months.
And what do I find?

254
00:16:57,491 --> 00:16:59,324
The streets are swept,

255
00:16:59,326 --> 00:17:00,959
industry is in fashion,

256
00:17:00,994 --> 00:17:02,794
you're dressed like a Turkish whore,

257
00:17:02,829 --> 00:17:04,245
and all because a man arrived,

258
00:17:04,298 --> 00:17:07,799
stood on the beach, and said please.

259
00:17:07,834 --> 00:17:10,251
- You're angry.
- I'm confounded.

260
00:17:10,304 --> 00:17:12,587
He offers them less in
wages than I offered,

261
00:17:12,639 --> 00:17:14,005
demands more from them in labor,

262
00:17:14,057 --> 00:17:15,724
restricts more from them in license,

263
00:17:15,759 --> 00:17:19,344
and yet despite all of that,

264
00:17:19,396 --> 00:17:21,680
he's won them.

265
00:17:21,682 --> 00:17:23,898
How can that be?

266
00:17:23,934 --> 00:17:25,433
I know it may be hard to believe

267
00:17:25,485 --> 00:17:27,819
given my appearance at the moment,

268
00:17:27,854 --> 00:17:30,689
but the experience of it?

269
00:17:30,741 --> 00:17:33,024
It ain't half bad, Jack.

270
00:17:33,076 --> 00:17:34,242
<i>Next.</i>

271
00:17:35,862 --> 00:17:38,196
Next man, please.

272
00:17:39,333 --> 00:17:40,365
Your legal name?

273
00:17:40,367 --> 00:17:42,200
John Rackham.

274
00:17:47,290 --> 00:17:48,456
What?

275
00:17:56,933 --> 00:17:59,050
The Lord Governor would
like a word with you.

276
00:18:01,521 --> 00:18:04,856
- <i>[people shouting in native language] </i>
- [breathing heavily]

277
00:18:08,228 --> 00:18:09,694
Watch him, please.

278
00:18:09,730 --> 00:18:11,229
I'll go fetch Fremah to tend to him.

279
00:18:11,281 --> 00:18:12,230
I said no.

280
00:18:12,282 --> 00:18:15,150
- I know you did.
- I don't want help.

281
00:18:28,248 --> 00:18:29,881
It'll pass.

282
00:18:29,916 --> 00:18:32,751
I'll just find a place to
weather it for the night.

283
00:18:32,753 --> 00:18:37,722
I understand that you do not
want anyone to see you this way.

284
00:18:37,758 --> 00:18:38,973
What I don't understand

285
00:18:39,009 --> 00:18:41,142
is why you choose to
suffer in the first place.

286
00:18:41,178 --> 00:18:43,094
You must have access to
better medicines than that.

287
00:18:43,096 --> 00:18:45,180
We've got access to
better medicines than that.

288
00:18:45,232 --> 00:18:46,848
This has nothing to do with medicine.

289
00:18:46,900 --> 00:18:48,316
It has something to do with medicine...

290
00:18:48,351 --> 00:18:51,269
I cannot look weak.

291
00:18:51,321 --> 00:18:54,773
<i>I cannot feel weak. I cannot be weak.</i>

292
00:18:54,775 --> 00:18:57,358
Not in front of my men.
Not in front of your men.

293
00:18:57,411 --> 00:18:59,611
Not at all.

294
00:18:59,613 --> 00:19:01,112
For some time now, I have been holding

295
00:19:01,114 --> 00:19:03,498
my entire world
together with both hands,

296
00:19:03,533 --> 00:19:07,168
<i>keeping my men in line,
seeing to their needs,</i>

297
00:19:07,204 --> 00:19:11,923
and the only way that
endures is if I look the part.

298
00:19:11,958 --> 00:19:14,342
And I cannot look the part
while being poked and prodded

299
00:19:14,377 --> 00:19:16,177
or while drooling through an opium haze

300
00:19:16,213 --> 00:19:18,296
saying who the fuck knows what.

301
00:19:19,766 --> 00:19:21,716
So I will endure this

302
00:19:21,768 --> 00:19:24,719
the way I have been enduring it.

303
00:19:29,726 --> 00:19:33,194
No one prepared you for this, did they?

304
00:19:33,230 --> 00:19:35,897
[breathing heavily]

305
00:19:35,949 --> 00:19:37,866
For as long as I can remember,

306
00:19:37,901 --> 00:19:40,151
I have been prepared for the day

307
00:19:40,203 --> 00:19:43,037
I would take my mother's place.

308
00:19:43,073 --> 00:19:46,207
To know that from that day forth,

309
00:19:46,243 --> 00:19:48,993
I would forever be the one who tends

310
00:19:48,995 --> 00:19:51,379
as opposed to the one who is tended to.

311
00:19:52,799 --> 00:19:55,750
You're frustrated. You're angry.

312
00:19:55,802 --> 00:19:58,136
You're tired.

313
00:19:58,171 --> 00:20:00,421
Perhaps no one else knows why.

314
00:20:00,474 --> 00:20:03,057
I believe that not even you know why.

315
00:20:04,478 --> 00:20:06,261
But I know why.

316
00:20:12,235 --> 00:20:15,403
The crown is always a burden...

317
00:20:17,991 --> 00:20:22,494
but it cannot be borne
if you cannot stand.

318
00:20:28,201 --> 00:20:32,003
<i>[waves crashing]</i>

319
00:20:32,038 --> 00:20:34,172
Nearly dismasted in a storm...

320
00:20:34,207 --> 00:20:36,257
a storm you chased after.

321
00:20:36,293 --> 00:20:38,927
Nearly starved to death in the doldrums.

322
00:20:38,962 --> 00:20:40,295
Nearly executed by them.

323
00:20:42,215 --> 00:20:45,300
Either you are unkillable, friend,

324
00:20:45,352 --> 00:20:47,435
or way overdue.

325
00:20:49,189 --> 00:20:52,307
One way or another, I am here,

326
00:20:52,359 --> 00:20:56,477
and there is much to discuss
about all our futures.

327
00:20:56,530 --> 00:21:00,565
What kind of future do
you propose that to be?

328
00:21:00,567 --> 00:21:05,286
I intend to gather forces
and move to reclaim Nassau.

329
00:21:05,322 --> 00:21:06,905
The conquest is always weakest

330
00:21:06,907 --> 00:21:10,241
when the conqueror allows himself
to believe that it is done.

331
00:21:10,243 --> 00:21:12,827
For Nassau, that point is now.

332
00:21:13,880 --> 00:21:15,330
Now, England may hold the island,

333
00:21:15,382 --> 00:21:17,248
but it still needs supplies brought in.

334
00:21:17,300 --> 00:21:20,301
It is still dependent upon trade.

335
00:21:20,337 --> 00:21:22,637
We will make that impossible for him.

336
00:21:22,672 --> 00:21:25,473
We will harass his ships.
We will plunder his supplies.

337
00:21:25,508 --> 00:21:28,893
We will force him to
bleed capital and support

338
00:21:28,929 --> 00:21:30,395
and the goodwill of
the men surrounding him

339
00:21:30,430 --> 00:21:32,764
until he is weak enough
to challenge directly.

340
00:21:32,816 --> 00:21:35,567
Until we can bring the fleet to bear

341
00:21:35,602 --> 00:21:37,268
and retake the bay.

342
00:21:38,405 --> 00:21:39,771
You know, when I called Nassau home,

343
00:21:39,773 --> 00:21:42,323
most of the men on this
beach weren't even men.

344
00:21:42,359 --> 00:21:44,525
<i>I sailed with Ben Hornigold.</i>

345
00:21:44,578 --> 00:21:47,445
<i>I sailed with Sam Bellamy.
I sailed with Henry Avery.</i>

346
00:21:47,497 --> 00:21:51,282
Feuded with them, stole from them,

347
00:21:51,284 --> 00:21:53,918
questioned their motives,

348
00:21:53,954 --> 00:21:57,288
but we all knew what we were.

349
00:21:57,340 --> 00:21:59,707
Then a man arrives
who would explain to us

350
00:21:59,759 --> 00:22:02,260
that what we've been doing
was wrong all those years,

351
00:22:02,295 --> 00:22:06,464
what Nassau ought to
be, what he could make it

352
00:22:06,516 --> 00:22:10,134
if we would all just follow his lead.

353
00:22:10,136 --> 00:22:14,722
And here you are again to do the same.

354
00:22:14,774 --> 00:22:18,943
You let it go well before its time.

355
00:22:18,979 --> 00:22:22,397
It was past its time.

356
00:22:22,449 --> 00:22:26,401
That you cannot see this
only makes it clearer to me

357
00:22:26,453 --> 00:22:30,655
that you never even knew
it in the first place.

358
00:22:30,707 --> 00:22:34,459
This fleet is all that remains of it,

359
00:22:34,494 --> 00:22:37,462
and as long as it's mine,
Nassau shall remain in its past.

360
00:22:37,497 --> 00:22:38,830
It isn't yours.

361
00:22:38,882 --> 00:22:41,332
It never was.

362
00:22:41,384 --> 00:22:45,003
Those ships, their commanders and crews,

363
00:22:45,005 --> 00:22:48,923
they were pledged to
my command, not yours.

364
00:22:48,975 --> 00:22:51,476
Oaths were taken,

365
00:22:51,511 --> 00:22:54,178
and I have come to see them honored.

366
00:22:54,180 --> 00:22:57,682
Do you honestly believe
that I would just step aside

367
00:22:57,734 --> 00:22:58,983
and let you make that claim?

368
00:22:59,019 --> 00:23:03,354
I honestly don't give a shit
what you would or would not do.

369
00:23:04,824 --> 00:23:06,741
The decision isn't yours.

370
00:23:06,776 --> 00:23:09,077
It's his.

371
00:23:14,584 --> 00:23:17,502
I've come to resume our compact,

372
00:23:17,537 --> 00:23:20,455
the one we swore upon
our lives to uphold.

373
00:23:20,507 --> 00:23:23,091
If you stand up and acknowledge it,

374
00:23:23,126 --> 00:23:24,509
this fleet will follow us.

375
00:23:24,544 --> 00:23:25,677
I'm certain of it.

376
00:23:27,380 --> 00:23:28,845
- You weren't there.
- No, I wasn't.

377
00:23:30,616 --> 00:23:31,296
But had I been there,

378
00:23:31,611 --> 00:23:33,611
there would be no
question about any of this.

379
00:23:34,920 --> 00:23:36,792
Had I been there, we would have mounted

380
00:23:37,136 --> 00:23:38,648
the defense that we had agreed to mount.

381
00:23:39,019 --> 00:23:41,037
Had you been there, you
would have seen their faces,

382
00:23:41,695 --> 00:23:43,194
the ones who laid their arms down

383
00:23:43,229 --> 00:23:44,896
and turned their backs on us.

384
00:23:44,948 --> 00:23:47,732
The ones who took our money for months

385
00:23:47,734 --> 00:23:50,234
and were happy to try and
deliver my head to our enemies

386
00:23:50,236 --> 00:23:51,786
for a little more of it.

387
00:23:53,123 --> 00:23:55,206
Nassau is dead.

388
00:23:55,241 --> 00:23:57,208
It doesn't deserve anything else from me

389
00:23:57,243 --> 00:23:59,377
or the men on this beach.

390
00:23:59,412 --> 00:24:01,746
We are finally free from it,

391
00:24:01,798 --> 00:24:04,248
and I see no reason to change that.

392
00:24:09,923 --> 00:24:13,091
If you wish to leave
this place, I'll allow it,

393
00:24:15,395 --> 00:24:20,064
although somehow I don't think
you have any intention of leaving.

394
00:24:21,184 --> 00:24:22,767
No, I don't.

395
00:24:22,819 --> 00:24:25,153
And I think you know that
I would never allow you

396
00:24:25,188 --> 00:24:26,604
to call a vote to settle the matter

397
00:24:26,606 --> 00:24:30,274
of who this fleet follows and
risk you depleting my force

398
00:24:30,276 --> 00:24:34,612
by luring away some misguided minority.

399
00:24:34,614 --> 00:24:37,081
No, I don't imagine you would.

400
00:24:37,117 --> 00:24:40,618
So we have one fleet
and two men claiming it.

401
00:24:43,089 --> 00:24:47,341
There is only one way I
know of to resolve that.

402
00:24:50,180 --> 00:24:53,347
Pistols, then swords.

403
00:25:04,944 --> 00:25:07,145
Captain Rackham.

404
00:25:07,147 --> 00:25:08,479
It's a pleasure to finally meet you.

405
00:25:08,531 --> 00:25:10,815
<i>Give us the room, please.</i>

406
00:25:10,867 --> 00:25:13,151
Drink?

407
00:25:13,203 --> 00:25:15,653
Thank you.

408
00:25:15,655 --> 00:25:18,039
I apologize for the
strangeness of this meeting.

409
00:25:18,074 --> 00:25:19,991
I know you and I don't know each other.

410
00:25:20,043 --> 00:25:21,325
<i>[door closes]</i>

411
00:25:21,327 --> 00:25:25,079
I know you... some.

412
00:25:25,131 --> 00:25:26,497
I read your book.

413
00:25:28,168 --> 00:25:29,667
Did you?

414
00:25:29,669 --> 00:25:31,052
Well, most of it.

415
00:25:31,087 --> 00:25:32,670
I confess, I may not quite have

416
00:25:32,722 --> 00:25:33,754
soldiered through to the end.

417
00:25:33,807 --> 00:25:36,340
But, you know, I got the gist of it.

418
00:25:40,230 --> 00:25:41,345
If you don't mind my asking,

419
00:25:41,347 --> 00:25:44,148
what did you take to be its gist?

420
00:25:44,184 --> 00:25:47,185
Wealthy son of a wealthy
man takes to the sea

421
00:25:47,187 --> 00:25:51,355
to prove something to
the parents, presumably.

422
00:25:51,407 --> 00:25:55,359
Seeks adventure, finds the
limits of his own capacity.

423
00:25:55,411 --> 00:25:57,328
Loses everything in the process

424
00:25:57,363 --> 00:26:01,499
and then stumbles upon a hell
of a story in the process.

425
00:26:01,534 --> 00:26:04,836
Please understand, I'm quite
particular about my library,

426
00:26:04,871 --> 00:26:07,872
but people seem to have liked it fine,

427
00:26:07,874 --> 00:26:10,174
and it seems to have
done wonders for you.

428
00:26:10,210 --> 00:26:13,427
So congratulations on all that.

429
00:26:17,934 --> 00:26:19,267
Thank you.

430
00:26:21,721 --> 00:26:24,555
All of that notwithstanding...

431
00:26:26,025 --> 00:26:29,727
you and I share an
experience in this place.

432
00:26:29,729 --> 00:26:32,563
And as such, I'm hopeful
that you'll understand

433
00:26:32,615 --> 00:26:34,699
why it is I brought you here today

434
00:26:34,734 --> 00:26:36,901
and what it is I'm about to ask of you.

435
00:26:38,738 --> 00:26:39,871
What's that?

436
00:26:41,791 --> 00:26:45,243
I know you removed a significant
amount of gold from the fort.

437
00:26:45,245 --> 00:26:47,295
<i>I know it is in your possession,</i>

438
00:26:47,330 --> 00:26:48,793
<i>and I need you to give it up... </i>

439
00:26:50,897 --> 00:26:52,376
or we're all dead.

440
00:27:03,897 --> 00:27:07,014
- [men muttering]
- <i>[seagulls screeching]</i>

441
00:27:12,438 --> 00:27:14,739
You can't win.

442
00:27:14,774 --> 00:27:16,324
[grunts]

443
00:27:16,359 --> 00:27:18,659
I hear you spent weeks becalmed,

444
00:27:18,695 --> 00:27:20,111
deprived of food and water.

445
00:27:20,113 --> 00:27:22,496
At your best, it would
have been a dogfight,

446
00:27:22,532 --> 00:27:25,666
but diminished...

447
00:27:25,702 --> 00:27:27,668
I'm not that diminished.

448
00:27:30,873 --> 00:27:33,341
He's been off the account for years.

449
00:27:33,376 --> 00:27:36,510
He'll be more vulnerable than
he remembers himself being.

450
00:27:36,546 --> 00:27:38,512
He's not that vulnerable.

451
00:27:40,099 --> 00:27:41,515
And for what?

452
00:27:41,551 --> 00:27:43,351
You subject yourself to certain death

453
00:27:43,386 --> 00:27:45,469
for an island full of
weaklings and ingrates?

454
00:27:45,471 --> 00:27:48,356
Those men will go where they are led.

455
00:27:50,727 --> 00:27:52,860
Rogers captured their
minds before you could,

456
00:27:52,895 --> 00:27:56,030
but let's not pretend that
they can't be won again.

457
00:27:56,065 --> 00:27:58,532
And let's not pretend that
either of us believes for a moment

458
00:27:58,568 --> 00:28:00,534
that I'm doing this for their sakes.

459
00:28:00,570 --> 00:28:04,155
I gave you my word.

460
00:28:04,157 --> 00:28:06,123
Shook your hand.

461
00:28:06,159 --> 00:28:09,126
Pledged to defend the island with you.

462
00:28:09,162 --> 00:28:12,830
But my pledge to him began a long
time before I ever knew your name.

463
00:28:12,832 --> 00:28:15,716
- What I owe him...
- I don't care.

464
00:28:17,470 --> 00:28:19,503
I don't care that you shook my hand.

465
00:28:19,505 --> 00:28:21,973
I don't care what you feel you owe him.

466
00:28:22,008 --> 00:28:25,926
This is too important to
be clouded by any of that.

467
00:28:25,979 --> 00:28:28,679
They took my home.

468
00:28:30,483 --> 00:28:32,433
I can't walk away from that.

469
00:28:33,519 --> 00:28:35,069
Can you?

470
00:28:37,106 --> 00:28:40,324
Forget me, forget Teach, forget loyalty,

471
00:28:40,360 --> 00:28:43,494
compacts, honor, debts, all of it.

472
00:28:43,529 --> 00:28:46,113
The only question that matters is this.

473
00:28:48,534 --> 00:28:50,034
Who are you?

474
00:28:59,512 --> 00:29:03,381
Spain knows about the exchanges?

475
00:29:03,433 --> 00:29:06,967
They do, and they are displeased.

476
00:29:10,390 --> 00:29:12,189
How do you know they know?

477
00:29:21,234 --> 00:29:22,817
So what does that look like?

478
00:29:22,869 --> 00:29:25,453
Return it all or it's the
Rosario raid all over again?

479
00:29:25,488 --> 00:29:28,072
- <i>[pouring]</i>
- Something like that.

480
00:29:31,661 --> 00:29:33,828
I understand why you did it.

481
00:29:35,381 --> 00:29:37,164
I know what it feels
like to lose everything

482
00:29:37,216 --> 00:29:40,167
and feel powerless to
do anything about it.

483
00:29:40,219 --> 00:29:42,670
The temptation to keep
something to show for it all,

484
00:29:42,722 --> 00:29:45,673
I understand it.

485
00:29:45,725 --> 00:29:49,226
But it does not change
the reality we face.

486
00:29:49,262 --> 00:29:52,313
That you face.

487
00:29:52,348 --> 00:29:55,566
For I assure you, if
Spain invades over this,

488
00:29:55,601 --> 00:29:58,185
yours will be the first face they see.

489
00:30:10,783 --> 00:30:13,417
I heard Henry Avery's
name when I was a boy,

490
00:30:13,453 --> 00:30:17,755
heard the way people spoke
it... grown men in awe of it.

491
00:30:20,460 --> 00:30:24,628
I came to this place so
determined to do the same.

492
00:30:26,599 --> 00:30:29,800
That's not going to happen the
way I thought it was, is it?

493
00:30:32,305 --> 00:30:33,804
It never does.

494
00:30:38,644 --> 00:30:40,111
My advice?

495
00:30:41,898 --> 00:30:45,282
You want some say in
how they speak of you?

496
00:30:48,654 --> 00:30:50,121
Write a book.

497
00:30:52,325 --> 00:30:53,541
[laughs]

498
00:30:53,576 --> 00:30:57,661
Right now, what do you want to do?

499
00:30:59,214 --> 00:31:00,489
Do you have a pen?

500
00:31:02,244 --> 00:31:03,770
<i>ROGERS: He's agreed to cooperate.</i>

501
00:31:04,084 --> 00:31:06,034
One man goes into the
interior to deliver this,

502
00:31:06,036 --> 00:31:08,286
instructions written in
his hand to his partner

503
00:31:08,338 --> 00:31:10,872
to return to Nassau
and surrender the cache.

504
00:31:10,874 --> 00:31:12,874
He said she may be wary,

505
00:31:12,926 --> 00:31:15,343
asked there be only one
messenger to deliver the letter.

506
00:31:15,378 --> 00:31:17,178
Give this to Lieutenant Hersey.

507
00:31:17,213 --> 00:31:18,680
Have him prepare to
depart for the interior.

508
00:31:18,715 --> 00:31:20,848
I'll pass him details momentarily.

509
00:31:20,884 --> 00:31:22,717
He should be made aware Anne
will not be taken lightly.

510
00:31:22,769 --> 00:31:25,353
Well, neither will Lieutenant Hersey.

511
00:31:28,525 --> 00:31:31,109
I understand Jack was arrested today.

512
00:31:31,144 --> 00:31:32,894
I would like to know why.

513
00:31:32,896 --> 00:31:35,396
<i>[crowd chattering]</i>

514
00:31:37,734 --> 00:31:41,069
- <i>[waves crashing]
- [men chattering]</i>

515
00:31:41,071 --> 00:31:44,288
<i>[seagull screeching]</i>

516
00:31:52,132 --> 00:31:53,247
<i>[man mutters]</i>

517
00:31:53,299 --> 00:31:55,133
What happens if he loses?

518
00:31:55,168 --> 00:31:57,919
If he loses, he dies.

519
00:32:00,340 --> 00:32:01,923
I meant what happens to us?

520
00:32:03,977 --> 00:32:05,343
I don't know.

521
00:32:06,513 --> 00:32:09,263
Probably given a chance
to join the fleet,

522
00:32:09,315 --> 00:32:11,849
fold in, and go back on the account.

523
00:32:13,686 --> 00:32:17,739
When your men entreated
me to join your crew,

524
00:32:17,774 --> 00:32:20,241
they said your captain
was a man worth following.

525
00:32:20,276 --> 00:32:23,611
<i>A strong man, a wise man, they said.</i>

526
00:32:23,663 --> 00:32:25,446
But right now I can't tell

527
00:32:25,448 --> 00:32:28,449
which side of this contest
you'd prefer to see prevail.

528
00:32:32,288 --> 00:32:34,956
Can you help me make sense of that?

529
00:32:35,008 --> 00:32:37,291
<i>[men muttering]</i>

530
00:32:38,962 --> 00:32:41,846
A few days ago I could
make sense of all of it.

531
00:32:43,633 --> 00:32:46,768
He was going to die and
we were going to be free,

532
00:32:46,803 --> 00:32:49,971
from the account, from him...

533
00:32:49,973 --> 00:32:51,773
[sighs]

534
00:32:51,808 --> 00:32:54,225
With all the shit he's done,
the things he's gotten away with,

535
00:32:54,277 --> 00:32:55,359
that would have been fair.

536
00:32:55,395 --> 00:32:57,395
That would have been right.

537
00:32:57,447 --> 00:32:59,480
I think part of the reason

538
00:32:59,482 --> 00:33:03,201
I've been able to stand by his side

539
00:33:03,236 --> 00:33:05,069
is that I wanted to make
sure I've got a good view

540
00:33:05,121 --> 00:33:08,489
of the moment the world
finally catches up to him...

541
00:33:10,710 --> 00:33:13,377
and this story starts
to make sense again.

542
00:33:13,413 --> 00:33:15,830
This is a matter of honor

543
00:33:15,882 --> 00:33:18,466
to be settled once and for
good in the here and now.

544
00:33:18,501 --> 00:33:20,501
The parties have agreed to combat

545
00:33:20,553 --> 00:33:22,336
and have accepted common practice.

546
00:33:22,388 --> 00:33:24,005
<i>The parties have further agreed</i>

547
00:33:24,007 --> 00:33:27,341
<i>there will be no
quarter asked nor given.</i>

548
00:33:48,198 --> 00:33:49,864
[exhales]

549
00:33:55,588 --> 00:33:58,005
<i>MAN: Cock your pistols!</i>

550
00:33:58,041 --> 00:33:59,540
[hammer clicks]

551
00:34:00,677 --> 00:34:01,843
[hammer clicks]

552
00:34:01,878 --> 00:34:03,127
From this moment,

553
00:34:03,179 --> 00:34:05,880
<i>there's to be no movement
until a count of three.</i>

554
00:34:08,601 --> 00:34:10,434
<i>One... </i>

555
00:34:10,470 --> 00:34:12,019
<i>two... </i>

556
00:34:12,055 --> 00:34:14,272
<i>three!</i>

557
00:34:14,307 --> 00:34:15,356
[gunshots]

558
00:34:15,391 --> 00:34:16,858
<i>[men gasp]</i>

559
00:34:20,446 --> 00:34:22,446
[gasps]

560
00:34:22,482 --> 00:34:24,899
[men whispering]

561
00:34:28,154 --> 00:34:31,739
<i>[seagull screeching]</i>

562
00:34:36,913 --> 00:34:39,797
[gasping]

563
00:34:44,087 --> 00:34:47,255
[gasping]

564
00:34:51,261 --> 00:34:52,810
[grunts]

565
00:34:54,764 --> 00:34:57,231
[men chattering]

566
00:34:58,434 --> 00:35:00,818
[gasping]

567
00:35:05,491 --> 00:35:07,275
[groans]

568
00:35:12,532 --> 00:35:15,833
[gasping]

569
00:35:22,458 --> 00:35:23,841
[exhales]

570
00:35:37,640 --> 00:35:39,941
[both grunting]

571
00:36:11,758 --> 00:36:14,842
- [squelches]
- [shouts, groans]

572
00:36:21,100 --> 00:36:22,733
[grunts]

573
00:36:34,697 --> 00:36:37,999
[grunting, panting]

574
00:36:40,753 --> 00:36:43,204
[grunting]

575
00:37:21,294 --> 00:37:23,077
Take him.

576
00:37:23,129 --> 00:37:25,746
And get the fuck off my beach.

577
00:37:44,934 --> 00:37:47,985
<i>[men chattering in native language]</i>

578
00:37:49,906 --> 00:37:52,106
If you won't take the opium,

579
00:37:52,108 --> 00:37:55,409
at least take this to bite down on.

580
00:37:57,163 --> 00:37:58,996
Just do it.

581
00:38:03,669 --> 00:38:05,252
[grunts]

582
00:38:10,126 --> 00:38:11,292
[gasps]

583
00:38:12,011 --> 00:38:14,795
[breathing heavily]

584
00:38:14,847 --> 00:38:16,297
[grunts]

585
00:38:22,939 --> 00:38:25,806
<i>[squishing]</i>

586
00:38:25,858 --> 00:38:27,892
[whimpers]

587
00:38:30,480 --> 00:38:33,147
<i>[breathing heavily]</i>

588
00:38:35,785 --> 00:38:39,370
<i>♪</i>

589
00:38:55,505 --> 00:38:57,922
<i>SILVER: The burden I
wasn't prepared for... </i>

590
00:38:57,974 --> 00:39:00,591
<i>[distant drums beating]</i>

591
00:39:00,643 --> 00:39:02,593
<i>SILVER: it isn't the men.</i>

592
00:39:04,063 --> 00:39:06,147
It's him.

593
00:39:08,434 --> 00:39:09,567
Flint?

594
00:39:12,104 --> 00:39:16,106
What he wants, what he needs,

595
00:39:16,159 --> 00:39:18,275
what he fears...

596
00:39:19,495 --> 00:39:21,162
the depths of it...

597
00:39:22,331 --> 00:39:25,416
<i>they are profound and dark.</i>

598
00:39:26,953 --> 00:39:29,954
I serve the crew best by tempering him,

599
00:39:30,006 --> 00:39:33,541
steering him where he's needed.

600
00:39:33,593 --> 00:39:36,010
I've descended into those
depths and connected with him

601
00:39:36,045 --> 00:39:39,880
so that I might be able to do so.

602
00:39:39,882 --> 00:39:43,851
But I am acutely aware that I'm
not the first to have been there...

603
00:39:45,304 --> 00:39:49,273
<i>to have been a partner
to him in this way.</i>

604
00:39:49,308 --> 00:39:53,227
And that the ones that have
seen those depths before...

605
00:39:55,698 --> 00:39:57,898
they never surfaced again.

606
00:39:59,735 --> 00:40:03,037
<i>Maybe their mistake was
in trying to do it alone.</i>

607
00:40:04,824 --> 00:40:07,458
Maybe to go to such a place,

608
00:40:07,493 --> 00:40:09,960
one needs another

609
00:40:09,996 --> 00:40:13,964
to hold the tether
and to find a way out.

610
00:40:18,804 --> 00:40:20,304
Maybe.

611
00:40:33,603 --> 00:40:35,486
<i>[door opens]</i>

612
00:40:46,449 --> 00:40:48,949
I know this cannot
have been easy for you.

613
00:40:49,001 --> 00:40:53,254
I know this is so far from how
you thought things would end.

614
00:40:53,289 --> 00:40:56,373
But I wanted you to
know that the end of this

615
00:40:56,425 --> 00:40:59,460
may not quite be what you think it is.

616
00:40:59,512 --> 00:41:01,795
How's that?

617
00:41:03,015 --> 00:41:04,265
When Anne receives your letter

618
00:41:04,300 --> 00:41:06,684
<i>and returns here with
what remains of the cache,</i>

619
00:41:06,719 --> 00:41:09,136
<i>Nassau will be secured,</i>

620
00:41:09,138 --> 00:41:13,807
<i>and everyone will know that
it is because of Jack Rackham</i>

621
00:41:14,193 --> 00:41:16,477
<i>that it occurred.</i>

622
00:41:18,864 --> 00:41:22,199
I'll have spared Nassau...

623
00:41:23,736 --> 00:41:25,202
and you think the story of it

624
00:41:25,237 --> 00:41:27,204
will be told long after I am gone?

625
00:41:27,239 --> 00:41:28,322
<i>I know it will.</i>

626
00:41:28,324 --> 00:41:30,457
I will make sure of it.

627
00:41:31,460 --> 00:41:34,578
Sounds a lifeless story to me,

628
00:41:34,630 --> 00:41:37,247
and one that requires
commitments before the fact

629
00:41:37,300 --> 00:41:38,999
to ensure its retelling.

630
00:41:39,001 --> 00:41:43,470
When the current story
unfolds, I assure you,

631
00:41:43,506 --> 00:41:47,224
it's going to get around all on its own.

632
00:41:47,259 --> 00:41:49,093
What does that mean?

633
00:41:51,347 --> 00:41:52,513
I walked into this place today

634
00:41:52,515 --> 00:41:55,816
stunned at how quickly
that man downstairs

635
00:41:55,851 --> 00:41:57,484
had completed his conquest,

636
00:41:57,520 --> 00:41:59,186
how thoroughly he had seemed to win

637
00:41:59,238 --> 00:42:01,689
just about everyone I
know over to his side.

638
00:42:01,741 --> 00:42:06,243
The truth of the matter is
there's been no conquest.

639
00:42:06,278 --> 00:42:08,195
It's only the appearance of one.

640
00:42:08,247 --> 00:42:11,699
For conquest is an
either/or proposition.

641
00:42:11,751 --> 00:42:14,168
Either you have it or you do not.

642
00:42:14,203 --> 00:42:15,753
It would appear that without that cache,

643
00:42:15,788 --> 00:42:17,371
he most certainly does not.

644
00:42:20,042 --> 00:42:21,375
Jack, what did you do?

645
00:42:23,295 --> 00:42:24,294
I sent word to Anne

646
00:42:24,347 --> 00:42:27,348
<i>to take the cache and disappear.</i>

647
00:42:32,271 --> 00:42:36,607
No. The governor saw your letter to her.

648
00:42:36,642 --> 00:42:39,393
You don't think I can
convey a thought to Anne

649
00:42:39,445 --> 00:42:41,228
comprehensible only to her?

650
00:42:41,280 --> 00:42:42,813
A thought as simple as "run"?

651
00:42:42,865 --> 00:42:45,366
A letter that said everything
the governor wished it to say

652
00:42:45,401 --> 00:42:46,650
in exactly the way he'd want to say it

653
00:42:46,702 --> 00:42:49,319
would not sound like
anything I'd ever say.

654
00:42:49,372 --> 00:42:51,488
<i>A thought here or two
between the lines... </i>

655
00:42:51,540 --> 00:42:53,407
<i>I assure you, she understood.</i>

656
00:42:56,746 --> 00:42:59,747
So I have begun the duel

657
00:42:59,749 --> 00:43:01,965
between myself and our Lord Governor.

658
00:43:02,001 --> 00:43:04,051
<i>The rules are simple.</i>

659
00:43:04,086 --> 00:43:05,753
<i>I will deny him the cache.</i>

660
00:43:05,755 --> 00:43:09,256
<i>No matter what sort of inducements
he offers or pain he inflicts,</i>

661
00:43:09,308 --> 00:43:10,891
I will deny him the cache,

662
00:43:10,926 --> 00:43:14,094
and so I will deny him the victory.

663
00:43:14,146 --> 00:43:18,148
And in doing so, I will ensure that
whatever Nassau is come Christmas,

664
00:43:19,902 --> 00:43:21,769
English will be not it.

665
00:43:21,821 --> 00:43:24,271
[silent]

666
00:43:32,832 --> 00:43:34,281
Do not do this.

667
00:43:34,333 --> 00:43:36,366
It's done.

668
00:43:48,514 --> 00:43:50,798
<i>RACKHAM: So, one of two
outcomes will result.</i>

669
00:43:50,850 --> 00:43:52,966
Rogers will understand his defeat

670
00:43:52,968 --> 00:43:55,102
to be ultimately inevitable
and leave this place,

671
00:43:55,137 --> 00:43:57,137
in which case I'll have it back.

672
00:43:57,139 --> 00:44:01,024
Or he'll stubbornly refuse

673
00:44:01,060 --> 00:44:04,194
<i>and eventually Spain will
raze this place to the ground.</i>

674
00:44:04,230 --> 00:44:05,946
<i>The English flag will burn,</i>

675
00:44:05,981 --> 00:44:08,782
and a second pirate
republic will be born

676
00:44:08,818 --> 00:44:10,033
from the ashes of the first.

677
00:44:10,069 --> 00:44:11,985
Only this time, every
man who calls it home

678
00:44:12,037 --> 00:44:14,655
will know it came about because of me.

679
00:44:19,662 --> 00:44:22,913
- <i>[crickets chirping]
- [people chattering in native language]</i>

680
00:44:41,650 --> 00:44:42,816
I worry...

681
00:44:44,103 --> 00:44:46,520
that we have made a terrible mistake.

682
00:44:46,522 --> 00:44:48,906
I see what you see in them...

683
00:44:48,941 --> 00:44:50,941
Silver and Flint.

684
00:44:50,993 --> 00:44:54,361
But their relationship is so volatile

685
00:44:54,413 --> 00:44:57,531
and we have put our
lives in their hands.

686
00:44:59,034 --> 00:45:03,370
Those men rose to their stations

687
00:45:03,422 --> 00:45:06,590
because they are peerless

688
00:45:06,625 --> 00:45:09,593
when it comes to shaping
the world to their will,

689
00:45:09,628 --> 00:45:13,714
in creating a narrative and wielding it

690
00:45:13,766 --> 00:45:17,885
to compel men's hearts and minds.

691
00:45:17,937 --> 00:45:21,388
<i>But the most compelling story</i>

692
00:45:21,390 --> 00:45:24,057
<i>requires a villain at its center.</i>

693
00:45:24,109 --> 00:45:27,778
And if either Captain
Flint or Mr. Silver

694
00:45:29,815 --> 00:45:31,281
sees the other as a villain...

695
00:45:31,317 --> 00:45:33,867
or worse...

696
00:45:33,903 --> 00:45:36,069
us as that...

697
00:45:36,121 --> 00:45:39,239
<i>then all is lost.</i>

698
00:45:41,160 --> 00:45:45,879
They are of great value to us,

699
00:45:45,915 --> 00:45:50,584
but they must be managed
by us to avoid that outcome.

700
00:45:52,171 --> 00:45:53,420
How?

701
00:45:57,343 --> 00:45:59,426
I wish...

702
00:45:59,428 --> 00:46:03,513
you and I had not been so
separate all those years.

703
00:46:06,185 --> 00:46:08,485
I wish I could have found a way

704
00:46:08,520 --> 00:46:12,356
to be a better father to you.

705
00:46:14,493 --> 00:46:18,278
<i>But over time, I was determined</i>

706
00:46:18,330 --> 00:46:20,781
<i>to leave you something behind,</i>

707
00:46:20,833 --> 00:46:22,282
to give you the one thing

708
00:46:22,334 --> 00:46:26,420
that no one could ever take away...

709
00:46:27,957 --> 00:46:30,007
and that would make you strong enough

710
00:46:30,042 --> 00:46:33,710
to understand their world,

711
00:46:33,762 --> 00:46:36,296
interact with their world...

712
00:46:37,182 --> 00:46:41,602
wage war on their world.

713
00:46:41,637 --> 00:46:44,805
<i>But if their identity
lies in their stories,</i>

714
00:46:44,807 --> 00:46:46,056
<i>I wanted you to know them</i>

715
00:46:46,108 --> 00:46:49,476
<i>so that when we are ready
to call them enemies,</i>

716
00:46:49,528 --> 00:46:52,312
<i>you would be ready for it.</i>

717
00:46:52,314 --> 00:46:55,065
<i>The villain makes the story.</i>

718
00:46:55,117 --> 00:46:56,650
<i>So to manage our current partners,</i>

719
00:46:56,652 --> 00:47:00,237
<i>we must ensure that we
all agree at all times</i>

720
00:47:00,289 --> 00:47:03,206
<i>who our common villain is.</i>

721
00:47:06,745 --> 00:47:09,162
<i>MAN: The fugitive's name is Anne Bonny.</i>

722
00:47:09,164 --> 00:47:11,498
<i>She's going for a capture of £500.</i>

723
00:47:11,550 --> 00:47:14,134
[chattering]

724
00:47:14,169 --> 00:47:16,837
MAN: ... several miles away
on the road out of town.

725
00:47:16,839 --> 00:47:19,006
<i>[chatter continues]</i>

726
00:47:21,226 --> 00:47:23,393
<i>[horse neighs, hoofbeats depart]</i>

727
00:47:23,429 --> 00:47:25,062
Earlier today,

728
00:47:25,097 --> 00:47:28,398
before we knew Rackham
was still on the island,

729
00:47:28,434 --> 00:47:32,519
you seemed confident that we could
locate him and his friend in time.

730
00:47:33,238 --> 00:47:34,354
You said it was possible

731
00:47:34,356 --> 00:47:38,158
because they didn't know
that we were looking for them.

732
00:47:38,193 --> 00:47:42,329
Why do I get the feeling,
now that they do know,

733
00:47:42,364 --> 00:47:44,665
now that they've made
it their personal crusade

734
00:47:44,700 --> 00:47:46,416
to see this regime fail,

735
00:47:46,452 --> 00:47:49,086
that your estimate will
be far less optimistic?

736
00:47:51,757 --> 00:47:53,040
The militia will help.

737
00:47:53,092 --> 00:47:55,042
It will keep the pressure on,
and perhaps we'll get lucky.

738
00:47:55,094 --> 00:47:57,544
<i>But if we don't, then you
may have to be prepared... </i>

739
00:47:57,596 --> 00:48:00,180
Oh, I'm prepared to do anything.

740
00:48:03,435 --> 00:48:07,354
Anne Bonny must be found.

741
00:48:07,389 --> 00:48:10,440
The cache must be found.

742
00:48:10,476 --> 00:48:12,693
Right now, that is all that matters.

743
00:48:15,197 --> 00:48:17,397
And that said,

744
00:48:17,399 --> 00:48:19,316
the goodwill that we have engendered

745
00:48:19,368 --> 00:48:23,453
among the people of Nassau
is not without limits.

746
00:48:23,489 --> 00:48:27,374
The longer this drags out,
the riskier it becomes,

747
00:48:27,409 --> 00:48:30,293
because if I find that money
only to lose the street...

748
00:48:30,329 --> 00:48:31,828
You will not.

749
00:48:33,749 --> 00:48:37,968
If you have me, then
you have the street.

750
00:48:38,003 --> 00:48:40,754
I am all the reassurance they need.

751
00:48:40,756 --> 00:48:45,425
Yes, Jack and Anne were
my partners, my friends.

752
00:48:47,646 --> 00:48:48,812
More.

753
00:48:49,565 --> 00:48:50,931
But now they have made themselves

754
00:48:50,983 --> 00:48:52,566
something else to me.

755
00:48:52,601 --> 00:48:55,936
I have sacrificed too much
to build something here.

756
00:48:55,988 --> 00:48:59,322
I will not let them take it away.

757
00:49:12,087 --> 00:49:14,371
[bell ringing]

758
00:49:36,645 --> 00:49:40,981
All he ever did was
offer me his friendship.

759
00:49:40,983 --> 00:49:45,485
I cast him aside once,
spent years regretting it.

760
00:49:46,955 --> 00:49:49,623
And now here we are again.

761
00:49:52,377 --> 00:49:54,578
Tell me I didn't do it for nothing.

762
00:49:56,832 --> 00:49:58,882
Well, I won't lie to you.

763
00:50:00,169 --> 00:50:01,635
It would have helped having the fleet.

764
00:50:08,760 --> 00:50:13,513
We have assets, we have allies.

765
00:50:13,565 --> 00:50:16,433
The question is what we make of them.

766
00:50:16,485 --> 00:50:19,436
I may be able to help in that regard.

767
00:50:20,606 --> 00:50:23,940
Something to add to our pool of assets.

768
00:50:25,944 --> 00:50:30,080
Before Ocracoke, we came upon a prize...

769
00:50:30,115 --> 00:50:31,781
a Spanish prize

770
00:50:31,834 --> 00:50:35,619
ferrying a significant
trove of intelligence.

771
00:50:35,671 --> 00:50:37,787
